06129nam a22009735i 9780812294255DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2017    pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122942557 a10.9783/97808122942552doi  a(DE-B1597)488936  a(OCoLC)1004868654  a(OCoLC)992465458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR646b.P36 2017eb 7aLIT0150002bisacsh 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a822/.2092231 aPangallo, Matteo A., eauthor.10aPlaywriting Playgoers in Shakespeare's Theater /cMatteo A. Pangallo. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. "All write Playes" -- tChapter 1. "Mayn't a spectator write a comedy?": The Early Modern Idea of Playgoers as Playmakers -- tChapter 2. "Some other may be added": Playwriting Playgoers Revising in Their Manuscripts -- tChapter 3. "As shall be shewed before the daye of action": Playwriting Playgoers and Performance -- tChapter 4. "Watching every word": Playwriting Playgoers as Verse Dramatists -- tConclusion. "I began to make a play" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments  aAmong the dramatists who wrote for the professional playhouses of early modern London was a small group of writers who were neither members of the commercial theater industry writing to make a living nor aristocratic amateurs dipping their toes in theatrical waters for social or political prestige. Instead, they were largely working- and middle-class amateurs who had learned most of what they knew about drama from being members of the audience.Using a range of familiar and lesser-known print and manuscript plays, as well as literary accounts and documentary evidence, Playwriting Playgoers in Shakespeare's Theater shows how these playgoers wrote and revised to address what they assumed to be the needs of actors, readers, and the Master of the Revels; how they understood playhouse materials and practices; and how they crafted poetry for theatrical effects. The book also situates them in the context of the period's concepts of, and attitudes toward, playgoers' participation in the activity of playmaking.Plays by playgoers such as the rogue East India Company clerk Walter Mountfort or the highwayman John Clavell invite us into the creative imaginations of spectators, revealing what certain audience members wanted to see and how they thought actors might stage it. By reading Shakespeare's theater through these playgoers' works, Matteo Pangallo contributes a new category of evidence to our understanding of the relationships between the early modern stage, its plays, and its audiences. More broadly, he shows how the rise of England's first commercialized culture industry also gave rise to the first generation of participatory consumers and their attempts to engage with mainstream culture by writing early modern "fan fiction."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aAmateurism. 0aDramatists, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory andcriticism. 0aTheater audienceszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheater audienceszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZD